{"created":"2015-04-30T15:03:57+00:00","modified":"2015-04-30T19:44:24+00:00","valid":{"from":"2015-01-15T21:52:35+00:00","to":"3015-01-15T21:52:35+00:00"},"hreflang":"en","guid":"a5f2a528-0654-4d0c-ac03-27f4fb669e37","title":"Sound Opinions Show","teaser":"Mary J. Blige, the \"Queen of Hip-Hop Soul,\" joins hosts Jim DeRogatis and Greg Kot for a conversation about her two decades in music, keeping it real on American Idol and hopping across the pond to record her new album The London Sessions. ","description":"   ANNOUNCER COPY: Coming up&hellip;the queen of hip-hop soul, Mary J. Blige &ndash; in a long one on one with Greg Kot. &nbsp;\nNEWS:\n&bull; Hosts Jim DeRogatis and Greg Kot talk about Garth Brooks&rsquo; record-breaking sales. The cowboy has again beat the king, Elvis Presley, as the best-selling artist of all time.\n&bull; Universal Music Group is selling two companies that distribute mixtapes to prisoners.\n&bull; The punk band Stereofire Empire is responsible for returning a stolen painting valued at&nbsp; $250K back to its rightful owner.\nFEATURE:\nMary J. Blige talks about her latest release The London Sessions, which has her collaborating with the hottest names in British soul and house music including Sam Smith, Emeli Sande and Disclosure. She also talks about using music as therapy, why she strives for &ldquo;no more drama,&rdquo; her stint on American Idol and reaching out to Amy Winehouse.\nREVIEW:\nJim and Greg review What a Terrible World, What a Beautiful World, the latest album from the Portland indie folk group The Decemberists.\nDESERT ISLAND JUKEBOX:\nJim plays a cover of Brian Eno&rsquo;s &ldquo;St. Elmo&rsquo;s Fire,&rdquo; performed by Laetitia Sadier of Stereolab and the post-rock group Ui. Former Ui member Sasha Frere-Jones recently announced he was leaving his longtime critic&rsquo;s post at The New Yorker.\nYOUR SOUND OPINIONS:\nAt the end of the show we hear comments from listeners.\n","contentencoded":"<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml> <o